---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
import recap from "../img/recap-time-it.jpg";
---

<p-slide class="cover-internal" autoplay>
  <Image
    p-effect="zoom"
    src={recap}
    alt="Recap time!"
    class="alter-image-size"
    style="height: 10em; border-radius: 0.5em;--fragment-duration: 2.5s;"
  />
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <ul>
    <li style="margin-block-end: 1.5rem;">
      🤝 <span class="main-sub-gradient">MCP</span> — a standard protocol to connect
      LLMs with tools, resources and prompts
    </li>

    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🖥️ <span class="main-sub-gradient">stdio</span> — local process, zero config,
        ideal for CLI tools and editor plugins
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🌐 <span class="main-sub-gradient">HTTP</span> — remote service, multiple
        clients, deployable anywhere
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🔐 <span class="main-sub-gradient">OAuth 2.0</span> — required for public
        servers, use better-auth to avoid reinventing the wheel
      </li></p-fragment
    >
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Quick recap of the four pillars of the talk. MCP as the standard, the two
      transports and when to pick each, and OAuth as the auth layer for anything
      exposed to the internet.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">stdio or HTTP?</h3>
  <ul>
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🖥️ Local tool, CLI, editor plugin → <span class="main-sub-gradient"
          >stdio</span
        >
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🌐 Remote service, multiple clients, cloud deploy → <span
          class="main-sub-gradient">HTTP</span
        >
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🔐 Need auth for online clients like claude.ai → <span
          class="main-sub-gradient">HTTP + OAuth 2.1</span
        >
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        💡 When in doubt → <span class="main-sub-gradient"
          >start with stdio</span
        >, migrate to HTTP when needed
      </li></p-fragment
    >
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The decision tree is simple. Start local with stdio — it's the fastest
      path to a working server. Move to HTTP only when you need remote access or
      multiple concurrent clients.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<style lang="scss">
  ul {
    p-fragment:not(:last-of-type) li {
      margin-block-end: 1.5rem;
    }
  }
</style>
